Everyone learns useRef to grab a DOM node. Almost nobody learns the part that actually makes it powerful: a mutable box that survives renders without causing them.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Ask ten React developers what useRef does and nine will say "it gets a reference to a DOM element." They're not wrong — but that's maybe 30% of what the hook is for. The other 70% is the genuinely interesting part, and it's where useRef stops being a footnote and becomes a tool you reach for weekly.
Here’s the one sentence that unlocks it:
useRef gives you a mutable object that persists for the full lifetime of the component and whose changes do not trigger a re-render.
State persists and re-renders. A normal variable doesn’t persist (it resets every render). A ref persists without re-rendering. That third quadrant is exactly the gap a lot of React code falls into.
The mental model in one table
Survives re-renders?Changing it re-renders?Plain let variableNoNouseStateYesYesuseRefYesNo
When you need a value to stick around but you do not want the UI to react to it changing, useRef is the answer. Let's see where that actually matters.
Use 1: A mutable value that shouldn’t cause renders
Say you want to count how many times a component rendered — for debugging, not for display logic:
function Widget() {
const renderCount = useRef(0);
renderCount.current += 1;
console.log(`Rendered ${renderCount.current} times`);
return <div>...</div>;
}If you used useState for this, incrementing it would trigger another render, which would increment it again — an infinite loop. The ref just holds the number, mutating quietly between renders. You read and write .current and React never gets involved.
Use 2: Storing the previous value of a prop or state
A classic that has no clean state-only solution. You want to know what a value was on the last render:
function usePrevious(value) {
const ref = useRef();
useEffect(() => {
ref.current = value; // runs AFTER render commits
});
return ref.current; // returns the value from the previous render
}function Price({ amount }) {
const prev = usePrevious(amount);
return (
<p>
Now: {amount} {prev !== undefined && `(was ${prev})`}
</p>
);
}The trick is timing. The ref is updated inside the effect, which fires after the render is painted. So during render, ref.current still holds last render's value — exactly the "previous" you want. You couldn't do this with state without an extra render and a synchronization headache.
Use 3: Holding timer and interval IDs
This is the one I see done wrong most often. People store a setInterval ID in state, or in a local variable that vanishes on the next render, and then can't clear it:
function Stopwatch() {
const [seconds, setSeconds] = useState(0);
const intervalRef = useRef(null); function start() {
if (intervalRef.current) return; // already running
intervalRef.current = setInterval(() => {
setSeconds((s) => s + 1);
}, 1000);
} function stop() {
clearInterval(intervalRef.current);
intervalRef.current = null;
} useEffect(() => () => clearInterval(intervalRef.current), []); // cleanup on unmount
return <button onClick={start}>{seconds}s</button>;
}The interval ID has to survive across renders (so stop can clear it) but must never cause a render (the ID changing is irrelevant to the UI). That's the useRef sweet spot precisely. Store it in state and you re-render for nothing; store it in a let and it's gone before you can clear it.
Use 4: Avoiding stale closures in callbacks
Here’s a subtle one. Imagine a callback that fires later and needs the latest value of something, but you don’t want to re-subscribe every time that value changes:
function Chat({ onMessage }) {
const handlerRef = useRef(onMessage);
handlerRef.current = onMessage; // always points at the freshest handler useEffect(() => {
const socket = connect();
socket.on("message", (msg) => handlerRef.current(msg));
return () => socket.close();
}, []); // socket set up once, but always calls the latest handler
}Without the ref, you’d either capture a stale onMessage or be forced to tear down and rebuild the socket on every render where onMessage changes. The ref lets the effect run once while still reaching the current value. This pattern — a ref shadowing a frequently-changing value — is one of the most useful advanced tricks in React.
And yes, the DOM use too
For completeness, the thing everyone already knows:
function SearchBox() {
const inputRef = useRef(null);
useEffect(() => inputRef.current.focus(), []); // focus on mount
return <input ref={inputRef} />;
}React assigns the DOM node to .current after mount. Same mechanism, same object — it's just that the value happens to be a DOM element instead of a number or a timer ID. Once you see refs as "a persistent box," the DOM case stops being special.
The rule that keeps you out of trouble
Two hard rules:

• Never read or write ref.current during rendering (except lazy-initializing it once). The ref isn't tracked, so reading it mid-render gives unpredictable results and breaks under concurrent rendering. Mutate it in event handlers and effects.

• If the UI needs to update when the value changes, use state instead. Refs are for values the render output does not depend on. The moment your JSX needs to reflect the change, it’s state, not a ref.
That second rule is the flip side of a mistake I see constantly — reaching for useEffect to sync values that should just be derived or stored in a ref. If you've ever piled up effects to keep things in sync, it's worth reading why useEffect is a trap most React developers fall into right after this. The two hooks are misunderstood in opposite directions, and fixing both is how your components get dramatically simpler.

